        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Issued Every Friday<lb/>
                &#40;Telephone&#58;&#45;&#45; 243&#44; 39<hi rend="sup">th</hi>.&#41;<lb/>
                Three Dollars Per Annum<lb/>
                Editorial Department<lb/>
                The American Hebrew&#44;<lb/>
                498&#45;500 Third Avenue.<lb/>
                New York 12 Oct&#44; 1883.<lb/></p>
            
            <p>Rev. S. Morais&#58;&#45;&#45;<lb/>
                Rev. &#38; Dear Sir&#58;&#45;&#45;<lb/></p>
            <p>I have been trying to<lb/> write you for a week past concerning a<lb/> matter which may be of interest to you&#44;<lb/> but press of time prevented. At the time<lb/> we published our &#34;Sunday School number&#34;<lb/> last fall&#44; we had certain ideas we wished<lb/> to work out&#44; but which developed slowly.<lb/> Having little time just now&#44; I will tell<lb/> you briefly our plans&#44; and if they meet<lb/> your views&#44; will write more fully or<lb/> perhaps call on you concerning it.<lb/> We propose devoting considerable space<lb/> to Sunday School lessons&#44; to consist of<lb/> <del>ques</del> questions  &#38; answers &#40;or other form to be decided&#41;<lb/> after the style of the International S.S. Lessons.<lb/> The work to be divided up into <lb/> &#34;Biblical&#34;&#44; &#34;Post&#45;Biblical&#34; and such other<lb/> divisions as may be arranged&#44; each de&#45;<lb/>partment under charge of one person.<lb/> The space of at least 1Â½ col per week to<lb/> be devoted to it&#44; &#38; if we enlarge&#44; which this<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
                <p>Issued Every Friday<lb/>
                    &#40;Telephone&#58;&#45;&#45; 243&#44; 39<hi rend="sup">th</hi>.&#41;<lb/>
                    Three Dollars Per Annum<lb/>
                    Editorial Department<lb/>
                    The American Hebrew&#44;<lb/>
                    498&#45;500 Third Avenue.<lb/>
                    New York 12 Oct&#44; 1883.<lb/></p>
                
            <p>move will very likely necessitate<lb/> we would give over a page to the<lb/> purpose. This matter is to be set<lb/> up in style for reproduction&#44; so<lb/> that the same forms or plates<lb/> therefrom can be used in<lb/> printing such numbers of copies<lb/> &#91;&#94;&#93; &#40;of this portion&#41; as may be ordered by various<lb/> religious schools. A few gentlemen<lb/> have agreed to guarantee the ex&#45;<lb/>pense under certain conditions&#44; <lb/> and any profit that may accrue<lb/> from the sale of the sheets is to go<lb/> to the gentlemen who perform<lb/> the necessary literary work.<lb/> While being essentially Jewish&#44; it<lb/> is desired that these lessons shall<lb/> be written in a manner to com&#45;<lb/>mend them to all shades of Juda&#45;<lb/> ism&#44; leaving it to the individual<lb/> instructors to go into the details<lb/> more closely. Neglect on my part<lb/> when in your city last Spring<lb/> to speak of it to you caused us<lb/> some delay&#44; and it was your PS<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
                <p>Issued Every Friday<lb/>
                    &#40;Telephone&#58;&#45;&#45; 243&#44; 39<hi rend="sup">th</hi>.&#41;<lb/>
                    Three Dollars Per Annum<lb/>
                    Editorial Department<lb/>
                    The American Hebrew&#44;<lb/>
                    498&#45;500 Third Avenue.<lb/>
                    New York 12 Oct&#44; 1883.<lb/></p>
                
            <p>to the &#34;Record&#34;letter that induced<lb/> me to write you without &#94; further delay&#44; and<lb/> this is about as close as I could<lb/> get to it. The gentlemen so far in&#45;<lb/>terested in the literary work are<lb/> Revs. A.P. &#38; H.P. Mendes&#44; <del>and</del> it is possible<lb/> &#40;but very unlikely&#41; on account of editorial<lb/> work&#41; that Dr. Mendes may assist. <del>The former</del><lb/> They have asked me to write you inviting<lb/> you to take part and ask<del>ing</del> what you<lb/> think of the idea &#38; in what way you <lb/>could aid. Before your letter appeared<lb/> Rev. Henry P. had prepared himself for the<lb/> Post Biblical&#44; and since seeing it he says<lb/> if you wish to take hold of that&#44; he<lb/> will yield to you with the greatest pleasure<lb/> &#38; find some other department for the<lb/> field is quite large.<lb/></p>
            <p>This will give you an idea of what we<lb/> propose&#44; and it will afford us much pleasure<lb/> to hear from you concerning it.<lb/></p>
            <p>With my best wishes for the coming year&#44;<lb/>
                I remain Yrs truly&#44;<lb/>
                P. Cowlen&#91;&#63;&#93;<lb/></p>
        </body>
